1
00:01:53,512 --> 00:01:56,647
<i>The Second World War</i>
<i>was in its decisive phase.</i>

2
00:01:56,649 --> 00:02:00,685
<i>The Battle of Stalingrad</i>
<i>was crucial.</i>

3
00:02:00,687 --> 00:02:04,188
<i>The Germans had barricaded</i>
<i>themselves in</i>

4
00:02:04,190 --> 00:02:05,223
<i>all over the city.</i>

5
00:02:05,225 --> 00:02:06,424
<i>If they had taken Stalingrad,</i>

6
00:02:06,426 --> 00:02:09,227
<i>they would have taken control</i>
<i>the Russian oil fields,</i>

7
00:02:09,229 --> 00:02:12,663
<i>and Stalin would have</i>
<i>lost his advantage.</i>

8
00:02:12,665 --> 00:02:15,700
<i>So he put his sick genius mind</i>
<i>into action</i>

9
00:02:15,702 --> 00:02:18,169
<i>into winning the battle</i>
<i>at all costs.</i>

10
00:02:18,171 --> 00:02:23,374
<i>Over 2 million people died</i>
<i>during that battle.</i>

11
00:02:34,620 --> 00:02:39,257
[screaming]

12
00:02:43,862 --> 00:02:47,465
[screaming continues]

13
00:03:02,648 --> 00:03:08,386
[yelling in German]

14
00:03:21,767 --> 00:03:24,235
[screaming]

15
00:03:27,673 --> 00:03:30,274
[indistinct]

16
00:04:28,300 --> 00:04:31,002
[machine gun fire]

17
00:04:38,944 --> 00:04:42,380
[yells]

18
00:05:09,074 --> 00:05:12,076
[screaming]

19
00:05:55,754 --> 00:05:59,990
[whimpering]

20
00:07:16,868 --> 00:07:22,640
[man humming]

21
00:07:34,786 --> 00:07:38,956
[continues humming]

22
00:08:19,598 --> 00:08:22,233
- [gunfire]
- [screams]

23
00:08:48,793 --> 00:08:50,594
[flicks lighter]

24
00:08:50,929 --> 00:08:56,567
We have no account as to how
this man Hans survived.

25
00:08:59,971 --> 00:09:00,971
This is his diary.

26
00:09:00,973 --> 00:09:04,074
I got it from a friend of mine
I grew up with in Scotland,

27
00:09:04,076 --> 00:09:06,810
who's now with MI6.

28
00:09:06,812 --> 00:09:12,049
The last entry is August 1944.

29
00:09:12,051 --> 00:09:12,983
Couple of days later,

30
00:09:12,985 --> 00:09:17,888
he allegedly killed himself
in a German psych ward.

31
00:09:17,890 --> 00:09:22,026
- How is your German?
- Serviceable.

32
00:09:36,341 --> 00:09:40,911
Okay, so why do we give a shit
about some lunatic's journal?

33
00:09:40,913 --> 00:09:44,715
This is not some search
for the boogeyman, soldier.

34
00:09:44,717 --> 00:09:49,119
This is about
biochemical genocide.

35
00:09:49,121 --> 00:09:51,188
Exactly.

36
00:12:22,240 --> 00:12:26,276
[heavy breathing]

37
00:12:48,800 --> 00:12:51,068
[screeching]

38
00:12:57,208 --> 00:12:58,909
[growling]

39
00:12:58,911 --> 00:13:02,112
Stalin was always
one step ahead of Hitler,

40
00:13:02,114 --> 00:13:04,782
trying to create
a race of super warriors.

41
00:13:04,784 --> 00:13:07,885
Fortunately his experiments
were all destroyed

42
00:13:07,887 --> 00:13:09,486
before the end of the war.

43
00:13:09,488 --> 00:13:12,189
Some high-ranking officials
think the Russians

44
00:13:12,191 --> 00:13:17,127
stumbled upon something
much more sinister.

45
00:13:17,295 --> 00:13:21,098
- The gas in the story?
- Yes.

46
00:13:22,100 --> 00:13:22,966
You know,

47
00:13:22,968 --> 00:13:25,536
I learned a lot about the Battle
of Stalingrad in training,

48
00:13:25,538 --> 00:13:28,839
when they burned that city
halfway down to the ground.

49
00:13:28,841 --> 00:13:32,109
Never heard anything about
poisonous gas though.

50
00:13:32,111 --> 00:13:35,579
That's because forces
napalmed the south side.

51
00:13:35,581 --> 00:13:36,380
Burnt it all.

52
00:13:36,382 --> 00:13:42,085
It was the only way
to control the infection.

53
00:13:44,956 --> 00:13:47,024
[growling]

54
00:14:10,148 --> 00:14:13,383
[growling]

55
00:14:22,894 --> 00:14:29,032
[heavy breathing]

56
00:14:36,574 --> 00:14:41,078
That's funny, sir. Is that
the new official ghost story

57
00:14:41,080 --> 00:14:43,413
to scare the recruits?

58
00:14:43,415 --> 00:14:44,047
I wish.

59
00:14:44,049 --> 00:14:47,150
Very few people
knew about the gas.

60
00:14:47,152 --> 00:14:49,920
They destroyed
all records of it.

61
00:14:49,922 --> 00:14:52,890
Nobody wanted to admit
any atrocities occurred.

62
00:14:52,892 --> 00:14:55,225
So there's no evidence of this.

63
00:14:55,227 --> 00:14:58,929
[scoffs]
You're holding the evidence.

64
00:14:58,931 --> 00:15:00,998
That's all we ever got.

65
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:04,468
Why are you telling me
about this big secret now?

66
00:15:04,470 --> 00:15:09,239
The last 24 hours,
reports come out of Bulgaria

67
00:15:09,241 --> 00:15:11,408
reporting an incident
that matches

68
00:15:11,410 --> 00:15:15,212
what's written about
in that diary.

69
00:15:17,215 --> 00:15:18,048
There's a base.

70
00:15:18,050 --> 00:15:21,051
On the base,
there's a munitions warehouse.

71
00:15:21,053 --> 00:15:23,053
This warehouse goes
8 floors deep

72
00:15:23,055 --> 00:15:25,555
and holds 80 years' worth
of weapons.

73
00:15:25,557 --> 00:15:27,691
With the Russians
and Bulgarians alliance

74
00:15:27,693 --> 00:15:28,992
after the Second World War,

75
00:15:28,994 --> 00:15:31,194
we think there's a good chance
that that gas

76
00:15:31,196 --> 00:15:32,963
is somewhere inside
that warehouse.

77
00:15:32,965 --> 00:15:35,565
So have one of our contacts
check it out.

78
00:15:35,567 --> 00:15:38,001
[chuckles]
We don't think the Bulgarians

79
00:15:38,003 --> 00:15:40,637
have any idea
what they are sitting on.

80
00:15:40,639 --> 00:15:45,142
We need to find it,
secure it at any cost.

81
00:15:45,144 --> 00:15:47,144
So how are you getting me in?

82
00:15:47,146 --> 00:15:48,679
<i>There have been a string</i>
<i>of arms thefts</i>

83
00:15:48,681 --> 00:15:52,616
<i>at several military bases</i>
<i>throughout Eastern Europe.</i>

84
00:15:52,618 --> 00:15:57,054
<i>Your cover will be as</i>
<i>Captain John McGahey,</i>

85
00:15:57,056 --> 00:15:58,055
<i>arsenal inspector.</i>

86
00:15:58,057 --> 00:16:01,224
<i>You'll be investigating</i>
<i>a robbery in the warehouse</i>

87
00:16:01,226 --> 00:16:03,026
<i>at the same base.</i>

88
00:16:03,028 --> 00:16:05,595
<i>Your job is to get into</i>
<i>this warehouse</i>

89
00:16:05,597 --> 00:16:08,966
<i>and report back</i>
<i>anything you find.</i>

90
00:16:08,968 --> 00:16:14,471
<i>Your contact will be</i>
<i>military doctor Ana Bennett.</i>

91
00:16:20,044 --> 00:16:22,279
<i>Anything with this insignia,</i>

92
00:16:22,281 --> 00:16:27,317
<i>you report back to me</i>
<i>and only me.</i>

93
00:16:36,361 --> 00:16:38,195
Captain John McGahey.

94
00:16:38,197 --> 00:16:40,330
- At ease, sir.
- Welcome to Bulgaria, sir.

95
00:16:40,332 --> 00:16:45,235
Pvt. Harold Miller at your
service. Let me take your bag.

96
00:16:45,770 --> 00:16:46,703
How long is the drive?

97
00:16:46,705 --> 00:16:48,772
- It's a couple hours, sir.
- Perfect.

98
00:16:48,774 --> 00:16:53,310
- Wake me up when we get close.
- Yes, sir.

99
00:17:39,390 --> 00:17:42,125
Most of the locals here
work for the base.

100
00:17:42,127 --> 00:17:43,760
It's the biggest employer.

101
00:17:43,762 --> 00:17:48,098
Yeah, looks like
they're thriving.

102
00:17:50,101 --> 00:17:52,769
Don't worry, private.
We were all young once.

103
00:17:52,771 --> 00:17:54,471
We have an hour for lunch
before we're meeting

104
00:17:54,473 --> 00:17:56,106
with the Bulgarian
commander Borov.

105
00:17:56,108 --> 00:17:58,642
I can have it brought
to your room or--

106
00:17:58,644 --> 00:18:01,478
I'll be skipping lunch.

107
00:18:01,512 --> 00:18:04,414
I need you to take me
to this address.

108
00:18:06,350 --> 00:18:08,652
Sir, I don't have
authorization to--

109
00:18:08,654 --> 00:18:12,422
- I just gave you authorization.
- Yes, sir.

110
00:18:47,692 --> 00:18:49,893
- Who let you in?
- Oh, hi.

111
00:18:49,895 --> 00:18:52,195
- We're here from--
- Don't sass me!

112
00:18:52,197 --> 00:18:56,833
You and your rowdy friends
better get out of here

113
00:18:56,835 --> 00:18:59,669
before I call Virgil!

114
00:18:59,671 --> 00:19:02,405
We'll only be a second, ma'am.

115
00:19:02,407 --> 00:19:04,508
Charming woman.

116
00:19:13,351 --> 00:19:14,818
Yes?

117
00:19:14,820 --> 00:19:16,419
Hi. Is Dr. Bennett here?

118
00:19:16,421 --> 00:19:19,523
Mommy told me not to
talk to strangers.

119
00:19:19,525 --> 00:19:24,361
Oh, uh, my name is John.
What's yours?

120
00:19:27,331 --> 00:19:27,898
Miriam.

121
00:19:27,900 --> 00:19:30,734
Hi, Miriam. See?
Now we're not strangers.

122
00:19:30,736 --> 00:19:31,935
Is your mommy home?

123
00:19:31,937 --> 00:19:33,603
She's asleep.

124
00:19:33,605 --> 00:19:37,541
Oh. I have some really important
questions to ask her.

125
00:19:37,543 --> 00:19:39,943
You think we come in
for a bit?

126
00:19:39,945 --> 00:19:43,880
Mommy told me not to let
strangers inside.

127
00:19:43,882 --> 00:19:44,814
That's a really good rule.

128
00:19:44,816 --> 00:19:50,587
How about you go get your mommy,
and we will wait here?

129
00:19:51,355 --> 00:19:54,357
Maybe you should come inside.

130
00:19:54,359 --> 00:19:57,360
My Aunt Koina
might try to get you.

131
00:19:57,362 --> 00:19:59,863
Sounds good.

132
00:19:59,865 --> 00:20:01,965
You look pretty.

133
00:20:01,967 --> 00:20:05,202
I made you coffee.

134
00:20:06,737 --> 00:20:07,604
Can I help you?

135
00:20:07,606 --> 00:20:08,939
Hi. I'm Captain John McGahey.

136
00:20:08,941 --> 00:20:11,975
I'm here regarding
that report you filed.

137
00:20:11,977 --> 00:20:15,879
Would you like
coffee or milk?

138
00:20:15,881 --> 00:20:16,913
No, thank you, sweetie.

139
00:20:16,915 --> 00:20:19,883
Is there someplace a little bit
more private we can speak?

140
00:20:19,885 --> 00:20:23,520
Mm-hmm.
We can talk through there.

141
00:20:23,522 --> 00:20:24,688
Great.

142
00:20:24,690 --> 00:20:25,522
Hey, Miriam,

143
00:20:25,524 --> 00:20:29,960
would you mind showing Pvt.
Miller here some of your toys?

144
00:20:31,329 --> 00:20:32,229
Sure.

145
00:20:32,231 --> 00:20:34,431
Thank you.

146
00:20:36,667 --> 00:20:38,935
Okay, who do you got here?

147
00:20:38,937 --> 00:20:41,905
This is Mr. Bunny.

148
00:20:46,310 --> 00:20:48,778
So I was looking over
your file and, uh,

149
00:20:48,780 --> 00:20:50,847
is it true you were
put on temporary leave?

150
00:20:50,849 --> 00:20:53,817
More like
indefinite suspension.

151
00:20:53,819 --> 00:20:55,385
Who suspended you?

152
00:20:55,387 --> 00:20:57,887
Bulgarian commanding officer,
Colonel Borov.

153
00:20:57,889 --> 00:21:00,757
He claimed my report
was grossly negligent,

154
00:21:00,759 --> 00:21:04,461
and I was liable
for what happened.

155
00:21:05,429 --> 00:21:06,997
What did happen?

156
00:21:06,999 --> 00:21:10,600
You won't believe me
if I told you.

157
00:21:11,569 --> 00:21:12,469
Trust me.

158
00:21:12,471 --> 00:21:17,674
If nobody believed you,
they wouldn't have sent me.

159
00:21:17,676 --> 00:21:19,376
I was on duty last week.

160
00:21:19,378 --> 00:21:22,545
And lift up.

161
00:21:22,547 --> 00:21:26,349
Thank you, private.
You can get dressed now.

162
00:21:27,018 --> 00:21:27,817
[coughs]

163
00:21:27,819 --> 00:21:31,554
- We might be able to save it.
- Might?

164
00:21:31,556 --> 00:21:36,293
You can start by
staying away from brothels.

165
00:21:36,295 --> 00:21:40,363
Dr. Bennett,
chemical emergency!

166
00:21:42,033 --> 00:21:42,999
So what have we got?

167
00:21:43,001 --> 00:21:45,869
They say a stack of barrels
in the munitions warehouse

168
00:21:45,871 --> 00:21:46,870
collapsed on him.

169
00:21:46,872 --> 00:21:49,906
Punctured lungs,
a few broken bones in his face.

170
00:21:49,908 --> 00:21:52,809
He was down on minus eight.

171
00:21:52,811 --> 00:21:57,314
[steady beeping]

172
00:21:57,316 --> 00:22:00,717
Dr. Bennett, he's gone.

173
00:22:04,522 --> 00:22:07,023
He's brain dead.
His heart stopped.

174
00:22:07,025 --> 00:22:12,395
The respirator is the only thing
that's keeping him alive.

175
00:22:12,430 --> 00:22:16,666
Time of death, 6:05 p.m.

176
00:22:44,028 --> 00:22:45,762
And the next thing I saw

177
00:22:45,764 --> 00:22:50,433
was him standing up
and attacking my nurse.

178
00:22:50,901 --> 00:22:52,469
[growls]

179
00:22:52,471 --> 00:22:57,707
[screaming]

180
00:23:20,731 --> 00:23:22,098
What happened to the body?

181
00:23:22,100 --> 00:23:24,801
- I heard they cremated it.
- Great.

182
00:23:24,803 --> 00:23:27,437
Colonel Borov said
he'd take care of the report.

183
00:23:27,439 --> 00:23:30,006
He wrote that the patient
was hallucinating

184
00:23:30,008 --> 00:23:32,842
and wanted me to sign off on it.

185
00:23:32,844 --> 00:23:34,144
It's bullshit.

186
00:23:34,146 --> 00:23:35,545
It wasn't drugs.

187
00:23:35,547 --> 00:23:38,581
The patient went ballistic
after he was dead.

188
00:23:38,583 --> 00:23:40,917
I insisted on revising it.

189
00:23:40,919 --> 00:23:44,487
He got furious,
accused me of being incompetent

190
00:23:44,489 --> 00:23:46,790
and responsible for both deaths,

191
00:23:46,792 --> 00:23:48,158
then suspended me.

192
00:23:48,160 --> 00:23:50,693
That's when I sent in
my complaint.

193
00:23:50,695 --> 00:23:52,996
Is there any evidence
of this?

194
00:23:52,998 --> 00:23:54,831
Photos, videos, anything?

195
00:23:54,833 --> 00:23:58,935
Whatever we had
was confiscated by Borov.

196
00:23:58,937 --> 00:24:00,837
What caused this?

197
00:24:00,839 --> 00:24:04,607
A biochemical substance
we believe is here on-site.

198
00:24:04,609 --> 00:24:07,877
Now what floor did you say
your patient was injured on?

199
00:24:07,879 --> 00:24:11,614
Lowest floor, level 8.

200
00:24:14,118 --> 00:24:15,552
With the U.S. taking over,

201
00:24:15,554 --> 00:24:19,956
most of the major duties
are split between both armies.

202
00:24:19,958 --> 00:24:22,225
How's that working out?

203
00:24:22,227 --> 00:24:24,461
Good.

204
00:24:24,463 --> 00:24:24,928
Really?

205
00:24:24,930 --> 00:24:27,997
Well, Bulgarians are upset
about losing control.

206
00:24:27,999 --> 00:24:29,966
And the Americans hate
that the Bulgarians

207
00:24:29,968 --> 00:24:32,569
are slowing down
the transition so much.

208
00:24:32,571 --> 00:24:36,639
Sounds like
one big happy family.

209
00:25:06,036 --> 00:25:06,769
Colonel.

210
00:25:06,771 --> 00:25:09,672
Welcome to Bulgaria,
Captain McGahey.

211
00:25:09,674 --> 00:25:12,242
Thank you, Colonel.

212
00:25:13,077 --> 00:25:20,016
Bulgarian army has always been
respected throughout the world.

213
00:25:20,018 --> 00:25:23,653
It is a shame they are giving
this base over to foreigners.

214
00:25:23,655 --> 00:25:27,857
Maybe the Americans boys will
teach you guys a thing or two.

215
00:25:27,859 --> 00:25:31,227
[shouts in Bulgarian]

216
00:25:31,662 --> 00:25:34,297
Colonel, I'm gonna need access
to all your warehouses

217
00:25:34,299 --> 00:25:37,667
and munitions'
storage facilities.

218
00:25:37,669 --> 00:25:38,701
I'm sorry, Captain.

219
00:25:38,703 --> 00:25:43,172
Those warehouses are only opened
in the event of war.

220
00:25:43,174 --> 00:25:45,241
Why would such a respected army
want to fight

221
00:25:45,243 --> 00:25:47,810
with weapons from World War II?

222
00:25:47,812 --> 00:25:50,013
With the string of robberies
you've been having

223
00:25:50,015 --> 00:25:53,650
in the past year,
the international authorities

224
00:25:53,652 --> 00:25:56,052
would like a more updated record
of your inventory.

225
00:25:56,054 --> 00:25:58,955
And since the base will be
turned over to Major Stone soon,

226
00:25:58,957 --> 00:26:01,691
that shouldn't be a problem,
should it, Colonel?

227
00:26:01,693 --> 00:26:05,328
The base, yes,
but not the warehouses.

228
00:26:05,330 --> 00:26:08,731
Those will still be
in my responsibility.

229
00:26:08,733 --> 00:26:12,569
Listen, Colonel, if you want
to keep your position here,

230
00:26:12,571 --> 00:26:15,038
I suggest you find a way
to make this happen,

231
00:26:15,040 --> 00:26:17,840
otherwise you may be
replaced a little bit sooner

232
00:26:17,842 --> 00:26:21,277
than you expect,
do you understand?

233
00:26:25,249 --> 00:26:27,650
Have a nice day.

234
00:26:33,724 --> 00:26:36,926
What does he want?

235
00:26:36,928 --> 00:26:39,295
To be a pain.

236
00:26:40,064 --> 00:26:43,967
Tell Vladi we need to meet.

237
00:26:43,969 --> 00:26:46,035
Understood.

238
00:27:01,885 --> 00:27:04,253
[children laugh]

239
00:27:22,673 --> 00:27:25,842
Thought you could sneak by me?

240
00:27:25,844 --> 00:27:28,945
You little brat!

241
00:27:40,257 --> 00:27:42,725
There you go.

242
00:27:44,762 --> 00:27:46,095
- Mom.
- Mm-hmm?

243
00:27:46,097 --> 00:27:48,064
I don't even like that cheese.

244
00:27:48,066 --> 00:27:51,801
Well, you know what
shopping's like on this island.

245
00:27:51,803 --> 00:27:54,737
I hate this island.

246
00:27:54,905 --> 00:27:58,775
So how was your
school carnival today?

247
00:27:58,777 --> 00:28:01,110
I don't want
to go anymore.

248
00:28:01,112 --> 00:28:03,246
Why not?

249
00:28:03,248 --> 00:28:06,416
They make fun of me.

250
00:28:06,850 --> 00:28:09,786
Because you're
smarter and prettier

251
00:28:09,788 --> 00:28:11,788
than all the other kids?

252
00:28:11,790 --> 00:28:13,956
No. 'Cause I'm American.

253
00:28:13,958 --> 00:28:15,124
They hate us.

